<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-sampling-statistics">
    <title>Sampling Distributions for Other Statistics</title>
    <p>
        The concept of a sampling distribution is not limited to the sample mean. 
        Every sample statistic has its own sampling distribution because its value varies from one random sample to another. 
        Examples include the sample median, sample variance, sample standard deviation, sample proportion, 
        and many other statistics commonly used in data analysis.
    </p>
    <p>
        Each sampling distribution describes how a particular statistic behaves when repeated random samples of the same size are drawn from the same population. 
        Some statistics exhibit greater variability than others, and their sampling distributions may have different shapes. 
        Understanding these distributions allows statisticians to measure the precision of estimates and forms the basis for statistical inference.
    </p>
    <p>
        In practice, the sampling distribution of the sample mean is the most widely used because many statistical methods are based on it. 
        The next section introduces an important result known as the <em>Central Limit Theorem</em>, 
        which explains why the sampling distribution of the sample mean plays such a central role in statistics.
    </p>
</subsection>